{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532172"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14656"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14656"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.01,0.05,0.02,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7349"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90603"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"3624"},{"type":"tags","id":"3685"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37278"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with fever and rigors. She has been receiving intravenous antibiotics through a peripheral cannula for cellulitis over the past three days. She has had multiple hospital admissions over the past year for complications following bone marrow transplantation, including infections and graft versus host disease. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. The cannula site is erythematous and tender. Two sets of blood cultures grow methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. A transthoracic echocardiogram shows no vegetations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antimicrobial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous vancomycin","Intravenous daptomycin","Intravenous flucloxacillin","Oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Intravenous flucloxacillin and vancomycin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) bacteraemia secondary to a peripheral intravenous cannula infection. The management includes immediate removal of the infected cannula and appropriate antimicrobial therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E remains the first-line treatment for MRSA bacteraemia in Australia. It has proven efficacy, extensive clinical experience, and is more cost-effective than newer alternatives. Treatment requires regular monitoring of vancomycin levels. The potential adverse effects include infusion reaction (\u0027red man syndrome\u0027) and nephrotoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaptomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative for MRSA bacteraemia, particularly in patients who cannot tolerate vancomycin. However, it is typically not used as a first-line agent due to its significantly higher cost and limited availability in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the organism is methicillin-resistant, meaning it would not respond to beta-lactam antibiotics including flucloxacillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E has activity against MRSA but is not recommended as monotherapy for MRSA bacteraemia due to lower success rates compared to vancomycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin and vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E in combination would not provide any additional benefit over vancomycin alone, as the organism is resistant to flucloxacillin. This would unnecessarily expose the patient to additional antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line treatment for methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus bacteraemia is intravenous vancomycin.","Peripheral intravenous cannula-associated infections require immediate removal of the device."],"references":["Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {26 Oct 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Davis JS, Petersiel N, Tong SYC. How I manage a patient with MRSA bacteraemia. Clin Microbiol Infect. 2022;28(2):190-194. doi:10.1016/j.cmi.2021.10.014 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34757117/","Lam JC, Stokes W. The Golden Grapes of Wrath - Staphylococcus aureus Bacteremia: A Clinical Review. Am J Med. 2023;136(1):19-26. doi:10.1016/j.amjmed.2022.09.017 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36179908/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90603"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14656"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90603"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T10:43:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T10:44:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7349"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Di